Pantheon Proposal

Interactive World Direction System (IWDS)

Abstract

The Interactive World Direction System (IWDS) is a proposed architecture for real-time collaborative creation and control of generative worlds. It integrates three emerging technologies:
	1.	Generative world models (AI-generated environments)
	2.	Conversational control agents (persistent AI director interface)
	3.	Real-time rendering environments (interactive simulation loops)

The result is a system where users can enter, modify, and direct AI-generated worlds in real time using natural conversation, effectively merging film direction, game engines, and AI-assisted simulation.

⸻

Core Concept

Instead of generating static media (images, videos, scenes), the system runs a persistent simulation world.

Users interact with the system through a persistent conversational agent that exists both:
	•	inside the scene as a character/interface
	•	outside the scene as a control system

This agent translates human intention → simulation modification.

⸻

System Architecture

Layer 1 — Generative World Engine

Responsible for constructing and maintaining the environment.

Capabilities:
	•	terrain generation
	•	architecture generation
	•	character generation
	•	object persistence
	•	lighting/weather systems
	•	physics approximation

Sources could include models similar to:
	•	Sora
	•	Meta Make-A-Video

but extended into persistent world simulation rather than clip generation.

⸻

Layer 2 — Real-Time Simulation Runtime

A world loop maintains continuity.

Functions:
	•	frame rendering
	•	physics updates
	•	character state updates
	•	event handling
	•	environmental transitions

Comparable infrastructure today includes engines like:
	•	Unreal Engine

However, IWDS integrates AI generation directly into the runtime rather than requiring prebuilt assets.

⸻

Layer 3 — Conversational Director Agent

A persistent AI persona that:
	•	understands the world state
	•	listens to user commands
	•	modifies the environment

Key traits:

Persistent identity

The agent remains consistent across worlds and sessions.

Scene embodiment

The agent can manifest inside the world in contextually appropriate forms:

examples:
	•	narrator
	•	holographic assistant
	•	character guide
	•	invisible system voice

Command translation

Example interaction:

User:
“Pause the scene.”

Agent:
“Scene paused.”

User:
“Rewind to ten seconds.”

Agent modifies timeline state.

User:
“Make the building blue and move the camera closer.”

Agent modifies environment parameters.

